(211, 72, 'Admin', 'hi Logan, <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThanks for providing me with the reference. We are collecting these forms according to our accountant ( I am not tax expert )<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, I went back and read the link you provided me. I guess there is a difference between the rebate mentioned on that article and the rebate that we are paying you. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the case a person buying a car from a dealer and the manufacture giving a rebate ( The manufacture here is the one who is running the deal and not the dealer ). <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn our case, these companies are paying us a sale commission, we are paying our members the rebate as reward for shopping through our website. If you clicked on coupon website before you shop through us, and he is affiliate to the same company, the other website will be getting the commission, and we can\'t give the rebate simply because we are the one who running the deal not the store. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nI am not sure if I was able to explain it well. Here is a link from the IRS regarding paying rewards that state we shall be sending 1099 form for any person getting $600 or more in rewards : <a href=\"http://www.irs.gov/uac/Form-1099-MISC,-Miscellaneous-Income-\">www.irs.gov/uac/Form-1099-MISC,-Miscellaneous-Income-</a><br />\n<br />\nSincerely,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPanda CashBack Support<br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.pandacashback.com\">www.pandacashback.com</a><br />\n', '2013-04-29 21:13:48', '', 1, NULL, '1'),
(212, 72, 'Logan Wise', 'Hello,<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThank you for your thoughtful reply.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe problem is that a rebate by definition reduces the cost of a purchase. Here\'s a hypothetical scenario:<br />\r\n<br />\r\nI buy a $30 coat from J Crew who has 10% cash back and that earns me $3. But, J Crew also collects 7% state sales tax which comes out to $2.10 on a $30 coat. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nMy total cost is:<br />\r\n$30 coat + $2.10 state sales tax - $3 Panda rebate = $29.10<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe rebate is treated as a reduction of the purchase price and additionally, the transaction has already been taxed. If I receive a 1099 form, I will be taxed twice - once on the initial purchase and a second time on the cash back rebate.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-wd/1027015.pdf\">www.irs.gov/pub/irs-wd/1027015.pdf</a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere\'s a quote from the first paragraph on page 3 in the PDF linked above (and also attached):<br />\r\n&quot;Section 61 provides that gross income means all income from whatever source derived. A rebate received by a buyer from the party to whom the buyer directly or indirectly paid the purchase price for an item is an adjustment in purchase price, not an accession to<br />\r\nwealth, and is not includible in the buyer’s gross income. &quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAgain, in the conclusion section on page 5:<br />\r\n&quot;(1) The portion of the credit card purchases that Taxpayers can either receive back in cash or request Company to pay to a charity does not constitute gross income to Taxpayers under §61.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease advise on how to proceed with the W9 form. If needed, my CPA can send an official document to your accountant citing the relevant IRS tax code. Thank you.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBest regards,<br />\r\nLogan', '2013-04-29 22:49:01', '84#1027015.pdf,', 0, NULL, '0'),
